Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C, bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with
@salt{0.25%tsp} for the orzo. Pop the @sweet potato{200%g}(diced), 
@baby plum tomatoes{125%g}(halved) and @British smoked bacon lardons{60%g} on a 
large #baking tray{} and drizzle with @oil{}. Season with salt and @pepper{}, 
sprinkle over the @dried thyme{1%tsp}, toss to coat then spread out and roast on
the top shelf of your oven until soft and golden, ~{20-25%minutes}, turning 
halfway.

Meanwhile, add the @chicken stock powder{1} and @orzo{180%g} to the boiling water,
reduce the heat to medium and cook until just tender, ~{10-12%minutes}, then 
reserve the @water{100%ml} and drain the orzo in a #sieve{}. Keep the pan, we will
use it next!

When the orzo is done, allow it to drain really well. Return the (now empty) 
saucepan to medium heat and add the @cider vinegar{15%ml}, drained orzo and a 
@chilli flakes{pinch} (careful, they're hot! You can always add more later). 
Cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}, then stir in the reserved water and 
@baby spinach{125%g}. Keep stirring until the spinach has wilted, 
~{2-3%minutes}.

Now stir in the @creme fraiche{75%g} - keep stirring!

> TIP: The more you stir, the creamier the orzo will become!

Cook for another ~{2-3%minutes} then remove the pan from the heat.

> TIP: Stir in a splash more hot water if it seems a bit dry - you are looking
> for the consistency of risotto!

Carefully fold through the roasted vegetables and bacon and the 
@grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g}. Use #scissors{} to snip in half the 
@chives{1}(snipped). Season to taste with salt, pepper or chilli flakes if 
needed.

Serve the orzo in #bowls{}. Snip over the remaining chives and finish with a 
sprinkle more @?chilli flakes{}, if liked. Enjoy!